Install-Module -Name Microsoft.RDInfra.RDPowershell

Azure Powershell:

Create Resource Group, NSG Rules, VNet, Subnet and Virtual Machine










Verify the infrastructure resources created in the Portal in the WVDLab-Infrastructure Resource Group

Create a Win 2019 Data Center VM

Standard_D2_v3 Win2019DataCenter has a price tag of $137.24/mo





Verify the DC01 VM created with a NIC, Disk and Public Ip

Configure the Domain Controller

RDP to the VM using the Public IP Address


The following step takes a Few Minutes:

Install-windowsfeature AD-Domain-Services -IncludeAllSubFeature -IncludeManagementTools

The following step will take a few minutes, and you’ll have to re-connect to the VM because it will restart

Install-ADDSForest -CreateDnsDelegation:$false -DatabasePath "C:\Windows\NTDS” -DomainMode “Win2012R2” -DomainName “xyzcloud.com" -DomainNetbiosName “XYZCLOUD" -ForestMode “Win2012R2” -InstallDns:$true -LogPath “C:\Windows\NTDS” -SysvolPath "C:\Windows\SYSVOL” -Force:$true

Log back on, this time with the domain FQDN:

Create Domain Accounts

Create another user with the logon name mary@xyzcloud.com

Create another user with the logon name tom@xyzcloud.com


Configure DNS

Create a virtual machine to host AD Connect

Standard_D2_v3 Win2019DataCenter is $137.24/mo

This step will take < 5 minutes

Install Azure Active Directory

Create Global Administrator User

Create a Sync Account

Go to portal.azure.com and sign in as AzureADSync@farzcloud.onmicrosoft.com/Temporary.Password and reset the password to Complex.Password

RDP into the AD Connect VM

Download the AzureADConnect.msi and Install it.

Use Express Setttings

The AD Connect Installation will take ~ 5 minutes

In the Azure Portal, Verify Users from AD DC are synced to Azure AD

Grant consent for the Windows Virtual Desktop service

Use the Global Admin you created in Azure AD

Assign the “Tenant Creator” role to a user account

Create a Windows Virtual Desktop Tenant

Add RDS Owner Role the Windows Virtual Desktop Tenant

Deploy a Personal Host Pool

AD domain join is used to join the Domain Controller

UPN is used to authenticate with Azure AD and must have RDS Owner Role

The deployment will take about 15 minutes

On Domain Controller Assign users to the Pool

Add-RdsAppGroupUser “XYZ Cloud” -HostPoolName WVDLabHostPool -AppGroupName "Desktop Application Group" -UserPrincipalName “mary@xyzcloud.onmicrosoft.com”

Add-RdsAppGroupUser “XYZ Cloud” -HostPoolName WVDLabHostPool -AppGroupName "Desktop Application Group" -UserPrincipalName “tom@xyzcloud.onmicrosoft.com”

Connect to the WVD Desktop using the HTML5 Client

Create a Storage Account and File Share

On the Domain Controller Register your storage account

Reopen Powershell as admin

This step takes <5 minutes


Leaving the OU empty...The computer account will then be created in the Root directly under your domain (not the computers OU).

join-AzStorageaccountForAuth -ResourceGroupName $ResourceGroupName -Name $StorageAccountName -DomainAccountType "ComputerAccount" 

-OrganizationalUnitName "<OU--FRIENDLY-NAME>"



$storageaccount = Get-AzStorageAccount `

        -ResourceGroupName $ResourceGroupName `

        -Name $StorageAccountName

Not able to see wvdlabstorage as a Computer name in Server Manager - Tool - Azure AD Domain Controllers (Since we didn't specify OU?)



In the Azure Portal, Verify ADDS is enabled for the storage account





Assign SMB Share Contributor Role to the WVD End Users



Assign the Elevated Access Role to another user. This user can then change the folder security settings at the NTFS level to customize them as required for the organization.



Verify access to the User Profiles folder by connecting to the WVD as one of the End Users and Navigate to <storageaccountname>.file.core.windows.net/<fileshare name>



From the Domain Controller VM, Remote Desktop to the Private IP of the WVD VM (host)

Stop the Windows Search Service



In Task Manager, verify that no WVD End Users are connected, or sign off the users if they are connected.



Delete the locally cached profile of the WVD End Users that may have logged on earlier.





Download the FSLogix Agent to the WVD Host VM



Extract from the zip download



Run FSLogixAppsSetup to Install FSLogix Apps







Open a PowerShell Terminal and execute the Commands to update the FSLogix Registry Entry - Set the VHDLocation to point to your FileShare


#Create the key New-Item -Path HKLM:\Software\FSLogix\ -Name Profiles –Force
#Create Enabled Set-ItemProperty -Path HKLM:\Software\FSLogix\Profiles -Name "Enabled" -Type "Dword" -Value "1"
#Create the VHDLocations New-ItemProperty -Path HKLM:\Software\FSLogix\Profiles -Name "VHDLocations" -Value \\wvdlabstorage.file.core.windows.net\fslogix -PropertyType MultiString -Force
#Create the SizeInMBs Set-ItemProperty -Path HKLM:\Software\FSLogix\Profiles -Name "SizeInMBs" -Type "Dword" -Value "32768"
#Create IsDynamic Set-ItemProperty -Path HKLM:\Software\FSLogix\Profiles -Name "IsDynamic" -Type "Dword" -Value "1"
#Create LockedRetryCount Set-ItemProperty -Path HKLM:\Software\FSLogix\Profiles -Name "LockedRetryCount" -Type "Dword" -Value "1"
#Create LockedRetryInterval Set-ItemProperty -Path HKLM:\Software\FSLogix\Profiles -Name "LockedRetryInterval" -Type "Dword" -Value "0




Open a Command Prompt and run RegEdit32 as an administrator. Navigate to Computer\HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\software\FSLogix\profiles and Verify that the Entries are present





Restart the WVD Host




Verify that User Profiles are Created on the File Share

As a WVD End User, Launch the WVD Desktop

In Azure Portal, navigate to the File Share and you should see a folder created for the user and the Profile vhd within the folder.






You can also RDP into the WVD Host VM and view the Profile under Disk Management

Adding Additional Users to WVD


To add additional WVD End Users (who already have accounts in Active Directory), log on to the Domain Controller VM, log on to the WVD Service usint Add-RdsAccount and then assign the new user with Add-RdsAppGroupUser

Add-RdsAppGroupUser "xyz Cloud" -HostPoolName WVDLabHostPool -AppGroupName "Desktop Application Group" -UserPrincipalName tom@xyzcloud.onmicrosoft.com




In the FSLogix Storage Account, assign the SMB File Share Contributor role to this user

$FileShareContributorRole = Get-AzRoleDefinition "Storage File Data SMB Share Contributor"

$scope = "/subscriptions/6ebd2f8c-21d7-4e7c-a99c-2673781552f6/resourceGroups/WVDLab-Pooled/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/wvdlabstorage/fileServices/default"


New-AzRoleAssignment -SignInName tom@farzcloud.com -RoleDefinitionName $FileShareContributorRole.Name -Scope $scope


$scope = "<get resource id of storage account file share from storage account properties>"


New-AzRoleAssignment -SignInName tom@xyzcloud.onmicrosoft.com -RoleDefinitionName $FileShareContributorRole.Name -Scope $scope



Assigning the role via Powershell did not work and needs some troubleshooting.

I had to go to the Portal to assign the SMB Contributor role.
